In August 2018, Elon Musk, the chief executive officer and largest sharehol=
der of Tesla Inc.,   tweeted: =E2=80=9CAm considering taking Tesla private =
at $420. Funding secured.=E2=80=9D As has by now been pretty exhaustively d=
ocumented, he=C2=A0was=C2=A0considering taking Tesla private at $420 per sh=
are, but he did=C2=A0not=C2=A0have funding secured. He ended up not pursuin=
g the transaction, ostensibly because shareholders didn=E2=80=99t like it, =
though also possibly because the transaction structure he had in mind =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0one in which Tesla somehow became =E2=80=9Cprivate=E2=80=9D but=
   kept all of its existing shareholders? =E2=80=94=C2=A0was not actually p=
ossible, or perhaps because he got bored with the idea and moved on to his =
next provocation.
If he=C2=A0had=C2=A0decided to push ahead with the idea, would he have been=
 able to raise the necessary $60 billion or so to finance the deal? I dunno=
, maybe? At the time that seemed like a lot of money. Tesla=E2=80=99s marke=
t capitalization last Friday was $601 billion, though, so in hindsight buyi=
ng it =E2=80=94=C2=A0or financing Musk=E2=80=99s plan to buy it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0in 2018=C2=A0would have worked out well. And Musk does seem to be=20
pretty good at raising money. And, at the time of his tweet, he had had=C2=
=A0preliminary conversations with Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s Public Investment =
Fund=C2=A0about financing the deal. They had enough money to do it. It=E2=
=80=99s not unreasonable to think that he could have gotten the money.
When Musk tweeted, Tesla=E2=80=99s stock went=C2=A0up. It had been trading =
at about $340 per share shortly before his tweet, and traded up to about $3=
80 shortly after; it soon sank back below=C2=A0the unaffected price. The US=
 Securities and Exchange Commission quickly   sued Musk for securities frau=
d, arguing that funding was not secured;   Musk=C2=A0settled for a=C2=A0fin=
e and a promise not to tweet material things about Tesla unless a lawyer re=
viewed them first. (He promptly   forgot about that.)=C2=A0
Also though some shareholders who bought the stock at its elevated post-twe=
et price sued Musk for fraud, arguing that they were deceived by his tweets=
. That case took a long time, but on Friday a jury   decided in Musk=E2=80=
=99s favor:

On Friday, a federal jury in San Francisco took just two hours to clear the=
 Tesla Inc. chief executive officer of claims by investors that he defraude=
d them when he tweeted 4 1/2 years ago that he was considering taking the c=
ompany private and had =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D to make the deal h=
appen. ...
Musk=E2=80=99s defense asked jurors to imagine a world through the entrepre=
neur=E2=80=99s eyes, in which a $60 billion deal to take Tesla private coul=
d be done on a handshake. The jury learned of his relationship with Yasir A=
l-Rumayyan, the governor of Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s Public Investment Fund, =
and a 2017 dinner with him joined by Softbank CEO Masayoshi Son, where taki=
ng Tesla private was discussed.
Musk testified that the =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D tweet was =E2=80=
=9Cabsolutely truthful,=E2=80=9D touting what he described as an =E2=80=9Cu=
nequivocal=E2=80=9D commitment by Saudi Arabia even though he had nothing i=
n writing. =E2=80=A6
Witnesses, including senior Goldman Sachs executive Dan Dees and Silver Lak=
e Management=E2=80=99s co-CEO, Egon Durban, told jurors that even a week af=
ter the tweet, they were still working to figure out how the deal would be =
structured, including who would pay for it.=C2=A0

The trial was a bit odd because the judge had already decided that Musk=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D tweet was=C2=A0false, so the tria=
l was technically about whether it was=C2=A0material=C2=A0to investors, whe=
ther they were deceived by the tweet. But Musk did not quite say that he=C2=
=A0was=C2=A0going to take Tesla private, only that he was considering it, w=
hich seems to have been uncontroversially true. (He considers lots of thing=
s.) The falsehood was =E2=80=9Cfunding secured.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0If you are an investor who bought the stock, you might say =E2=80=9CI=
 bought the stock because Musk was considering taking it private, and I was=
 deceived,=E2=80=9D but that would be wrong: You were=C2=A0not=C2=A0deceive=
d about that; he really was considering it.
Instead you have to argue that you were deceived by the funding bit. There =
are a couple of ways you could argue that, a couple of ways the =E2=80=9Cfu=
nding secured=E2=80=9D could have tricked you:
=09=E2=80=9CI thought his funding was secured, so the deal would happen if =
he wanted it to, but in fact he didn=E2=80=99t have funding and could never=
 have done the deal.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09=E2=80=9CI thought =E2=80=98funding s=
ecured=E2=80=99 meant that he had already done a lot of work in structuring=
 the deal and was=C2=A0serious=C2=A0about doing the deal. I understood that=
 nothing was=C2=A0certain=C2=A0and he could still change his mind, but I to=
ok the funding thing to indicate a certain seriousness, and I was deceived =
because he was just messing around.=E2=80=9D

Argument 1 was, I suppose, refuted by Musk=E2=80=99s testimony that he is v=
ery good at raising money and, if he=C2=A0had=C2=A0decided to move forward,=
 it would have been no problem for him to get funding, even though he did n=
ot in fact at that point have the money. After Musk=E2=80=99s experience bu=
ying Twitter Inc. last year =E2=80=94=C2=A0when he really did snap his fing=
ers and get together the $44 billion needed to do the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0I=
 can=E2=80=99t object too strongly to that.=C2=A0
Argument 2 was, I suppose, refuted by Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers=E2=80=99 argum=
ents to the effect of ahhhhh, come on, it is Elon Musk, nothing is all that=
 serious, he is winging it all the time, you had to know what you were sign=
ing up for if you invested in his companies. Even =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=
=E2=80=9D sort of telegraphs its unseriousness: The way to indicate that yo=
u have done serious work to line up financing for a deal is by=C2=A0deliver=
ing commitment letters from financing sources,   as Musk did when he bid fo=
r Twitter; just tweeting =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D indicates that y=
ou have a tenuous grasp about what the financing process would even look li=
ke.
Look! This stuff is contextual. Here is  the lawyer for the investor plaint=
iffs,=C2=A0Nicholas Porritt:
=E2=80=9CThis case is about whether rules that apply to everybody else shou=
ld apply to Elon Musk,=E2=80=9D Mr. Porritt said during closing arguments. =
He added that the stock market =E2=80=9Conly works because there are rules =
that keep people honest, so people can trust information in the market.=E2=
=80=9D
But is that right? The case was actually about whether investors bought Tes=
la stock at inflated prices because they were deceived by Musk=E2=80=99s tw=
eets, and in evaluating that question you might want to think about what Tw=
itter is, and who Elon Musk is. If Tim Cook had put out an Apple Inc. press=
 release in 2018 saying =E2=80=9Cwe are thinking of acquiring Tesla and hav=
e proposed a price of $420 per share, funding secured,=E2=80=9D the price o=
f Tesla would have gone up to, like, $410, because people would have taken =
that very seriously, because Tim Cook does not sit around saying nonsense i=
n press releases all day. But Elon Musk really does sit around tweeting non=
sense all day, so you can=E2=80=99t take him that seriously.
  [2]
 Does that mean that the rules that apply to Tim Cook (and pretty much ever=
y other public company CEO) don=E2=80=99t apply to Musk? Ehh, I guess? Sorr=
y? Here=E2=80=99s   Bloomberg=E2=80=99s story on the verdict:

The verdict isn=E2=80=99t likely to become a precedent that spurs more free=
-wheeling corporate disclosures on social media, said Adam Pritchard, a pro=
fessor at University of Michigan Law School. That=E2=80=99s because other C=
EOs will continue to use conventional methods to communicate about company =
business, he said.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CNobody does this =E2=80=94 only Elon does this,=E2=80=9D Pritchard=
 said before the verdict. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s incorrigible. I don=E2=80=
=99t think his behavior can be reformed. There=E2=80=99s just too long of a=
 track record of too much mischief.=E2=80=9D

You don=E2=80=99t have to like this! =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s incorrigible, so=
 we=E2=80=99ll let him do whatever he wants with no consequences=E2=80=9D i=
s a depressing conclusion. And yet as a matter of liability for securities =
fraud it does seem relevant? A few months before =E2=80=9Cfunding secured,=
=E2=80=9D on April Fools=E2=80=99 Day,=C2=A0Musk tweeted that  Tesla was ba=
nkrupt. A few months after =E2=80=9Cfunding secured,=E2=80=9D   he tweeted =
that the new Tesla Roadster would =E2=80=9Cuse SpaceX cold gas thruster sys=
tem with ultra high pressure air in a composite over-wrapped pressure vesse=
l in place of the 2 rear seats=E2=80=9D to fly. Neither was true. He has al=
so been promising fully self-driving Teslas imminently for years, and I gue=
ss the SEC is   looking into that, but surely by this point no one takes it=
 all that seriously. And yet if another CEO promised a feature for years an=
d never delivered it, people would feel deceived! Because that=E2=80=99s no=
t what other CEOs do, but it is what Elon Musk does. If you say enough fals=
e things, then no one will take you seriously, so your false statements can=
=E2=80=99t be fraud. Ahahaha boy is that not legal advice! It=E2=80=99s als=
o not quite true, in that the market=C2=A0does=C2=A0react to Musk=E2=80=99s=
 tweets, but in some sense that's not his problem. Here=E2=80=99s a juror f=
rom the trial:
=E2=80=9CThere was nothing there to give me an =E2=80=98aha=E2=80=99 moment=
,=E2=80=9D he said, later adding, =E2=80=9CElon Musk is a guy who could sne=
eze and the stock market could react.=E2=80=9D
Anyway Musk celebrated by  tweeting =E2=80=9CI am deeply appreciative of th=
e jury=E2=80=99s unanimous finding of innocence in the Tesla 420 take-priva=
te case,=E2=80=9D and I simply cannot believe   that 420 was not a weed jok=
e, but I guess the legal system has spoken.

