=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> SEC=E2=80=99s order</a> quotes Activision=E2=
=80=99s risk factors in its=C2=A0public filings, saying things like =E2=80=
=9Cwe may have difficulties in attracting and retaining skilled personnel o=
r may incur significant costs to do so.=E2=80=9D And it argues that Activis=
ion did not do a good enough job elaborating on that risk factor:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though Activision Blizzard disclosed the risk =
factors described above related to its workforce and how its ability to att=
ract, retain, and motivate skilled personnel might materially impact its bu=
siness, Activision Blizzard lacked controls and procedures designed to ensu=
re that it captured and assessed =E2=80=93 from a disclosure perspective =
=E2=80=93 certain information related to these risk factors. This included =
lacking controls and procedures among its separate business units designed=
=C2=A0to collect or analyze employee complaints of workplace misconduct. As=
 a result, complaints related to workplace misconduct were not collected an=
d analyzed for disclosure purposes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Additionally, during the relevant period, Acti=
vision Blizzard required that individual business unit leaders report certa=
in categories of potentially material information to Activision Blizzard=E2=
=80=99s Disclosure Committee. However, these categories did not include inf=
ormation relevant to Activision Blizzard=E2=80=99s ability to retain employ=
ees, such as employee complaints or incidents of workplace misconduct.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a result, such information often was not ac=
cessible to Activision Blizzard=E2=80=99s management and disclosure personn=
el, and was not assessed from a disclosure perspective. By lacking sufficie=
nt information to understand the volume and substance of employee complaint=
s of workplace misconduct, Activision Blizzard=E2=80=99s management was una=
ble to assess related risks to the company=E2=80=99s business, whether mate=
rial issues existed that warranted disclosure to investors, or whether the =
disclosures it made to investors in connection with these risks were fulsom=
e and accurate.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is no actual argument that the disclosur=
es were=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>accurate. (I guess they were not =E2=80=9Cfu=
lsome,=E2=80=9D but that doesn=E2=80=99t make them misleading.) The SEC=E2=
=80=99s position seems to be something like: Public companies are obligated=
 to collect information about workplace sexual misconduct and=C2=A0to discl=
ose it if it seems material. If they don=E2=80=99t disclose it, that is a v=
iolation of =E2=80=9CExchange Act Rule 13a-15(a), which requires issuers =
=E2=80=A6 to maintain disclosure controls and procedures designed to ensure=
 that information required to be disclosed by an issuer in reports it files=
 or submits under the Exchange Act is recorded, processed, summarized, and =
reported within the time periods specified in the Commission=E2=80=99s rule=
s and forms.=E2=80=9D If they do disclose it, and it=E2=80=99s wrong, that=
=E2=80=99s securities fraud.</p>
